| designation1 = National Historic Site of Canada | designation1_offname = | designation1_date = | designation1_number = | designation2 = | designation2_offname = | designation2_date = | designation2_number =
}} '''Fort Drummond''' was the site of a [[redoubt]] and [[Artillery battery|battery]] from the [[War of 1812]] and located within [[Queenston Heights]].<ref>[http://www.niagaraparks.com/heritage/plaques.php Fort Drummond]</ref>
The U-shaped structure was an [[Earthworks (engineering)|earthworks]] rather than a wood, brick or rock construction.
Built in 1814 by the [[British Army]] and named for [[Sir Gordon Drummond]], it was occupied by the Americans for two weeks in July 1814 during the [[Battle of Chippawa]]. It was later re-taken by the [[United Kingdom|British]].
A wading pond, added in the 1920s and replaced in 1967, is located within the site. The walls of the redoubt can still be seen.<ref>Guidebook to the historic sites of the War of 1812. p. 113</ref>
Other fortifications are located nearby, since the area was close to the border with the [[United States]]:
* [[Fort Mississauga]] (1814â€“1816) * [[Fort George, Ontario]] (1802)
